metadata.title: Cessna 310
aws::graph::propositions: Cessna 310 Aircraft Models and Variants
310M is a revised designation for the 310E model of Cessna 310.
310N is a model of Cessna 310 produced in 1968.
310N featured a revised instrument panel.
310N provided provision for optional cargo door.
310N provided provision for optional fuel.
198 units of 310N were built.
310P is a model of Cessna 310 produced in 1969.
310P was equipped with Continental IO-470-VO engines.
310P featured a ventral fin.
310P had a shorter nose gear leg.
T310P is a version of the 310P model of Cessna 310.
T310P was equipped with turbocharged Continental TSIO-520-B engines.
T310P was alternatively equipped with turbocharged Continental TSIO-520-BB engines.
T310P engines produced 285 hp (213 kW).
T310P had a maximum takeoff weight of 5,400 pounds (2,400 kg).
A combined total of 240 units of 310P and T310P were built.
310Q is the last short-nose model of Cessna 310.
310Q was introduced in 1970.
310Q had an increased maximum takeoff weight of 5,300 lb (2,400 kg).
310Q featured detailed changes from previous models.
From the 401st aircraft, the 310Q was fitted with a bulged rear cabin roof.
From the 401st aircraft, the 310Q was fitted with a rear view window.

text:
310M
Revised designation for the 310E.
310N
Model produced in 1968, with revised instrument panel and provision for optional cargo door and fuel; 198 built.
310P
Model produced in 1969, with Continental IO-470-VO engines, ventral fin and a shorter nose gear leg.
T310P
Version of 310P with turbocharged Continental TSIO-520-B or TSIO-520-BB engines producing 285 hp (213 kW) and maximum takeoff weight of 5,400 pounds (2,400 kg); combined total of 240 310P and T310P built.
310Q
Last short-nose model, introduced in 1970, with maximum takeoff weight increased to 5,300 lb (2,400 kg) and detailed changes, from the 401st aircraft fitted with a bulged rear cabin roof with rear view window.
